<p><br />
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Modus_Operandi">Modus Operandi</span></h2>
<p>Some rules I put up to discussion:
</p><p>1) I don't think anybody should "own" a bookshelf. If you care about a topic, then put some work into it. But don't fend off other people who might have the same interests.
</p><p>2) A bookshelf should offer more than just an alphabetical or chronological list of works. Add comments, links and cross references whenever you think it appropriate.
</p><p>2) If you elect a book to be "Editor's Choice" or just give it some stars, make sure it isn't just one of your pet books, but make sure the book has the quality to stand up before a wide and disparate audience. <a href="/wiki/User:Marcello" title="User:Marcello">highlander</a> 11:42, 8 December 2006 (EST)
</p><p><br />
to 1) I do not intend to own SF. I was just not yet able to get others interested (i tried in Baen's Bar). Hallvard Furuseth has joined so this is no problem anymore for SF.
</p><p>to 2) Already working on it.
</p><p>to 3) No problem with my choice (i hope).
</p><p><a href="/wiki/User:Robert_Marquardt" title="User:Robert Marquardt">Robert Marquardt</a> 11:55, 8 December 2006 (EST)
</p><p>For now i have added my name in the box title (mainly an experiment). I think a single box with the name(s) added in the content area looks better (i tried multiple boxes). <a href="/wiki/User:Robert_Marquardt" title="User:Robert Marquardt">Robert Marquardt</a> 11:55, 8 December 2006 (EST)
</p>
<dl><dd> We can put multiple editor names into a single box ... (use ~~~ as shortcut to add your name). What do the other people think? <a href="/wiki/User:Marcello" title="User:Marcello">highlander</a> 13:09, 8 December 2006 (EST)</dd></dl>
<p>Multiple boxes may be needed. I just added a Reader's Choice box to the Christmas section. We will probably also need the stars in different colors. <a href="/wiki/User:Robert_Marquardt" title="User:Robert Marquardt">Robert Marquardt</a> 09:40, 9 December 2006 (EST)
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="My_ideas_for_organizing_the_Bookshelf_tree">My ideas for organizing the Bookshelf tree</span></h2>
<p>First lets talk about what the Bookshelf should be. It should provide fast and structured access to the books of PG. A tree of index pages is the obvious choice. The tree should be not too deep.</p>
<p>Now structured access means several possible structures. The first choice is structure by genre. This is what we currently have. Other structures can be added later.</p>
<p>The most basic structure for the books is fiction and non-fiction. My proposal is to separate this into two trees, ie two links on the main page for a "Fiction Bookshelf" and a "Non-Fiction Bookshelf". An index page containing only links to these wo category would make the tree too deep and would not be visually pleasing because only two links is a bleak and empty page suggesting that the following pages are equally bleak and empty.</p>
<p>For the pages of Fiction we have two different structurings. Inclusive and exclusive. That is a Crime section would contain all the books of the sub-genres and sub-sections of Detective and Mystery. Exclusive structuring for the SF section where i want to put the pre-Verne books on a deeper level of the tree. This will allow books as early as possible in the tree while banning the less interesting/popular works down the tree. All in all we will have three kinds of pages. Links-only pages, -and-content pages and content-only pages.</p>
<p>The root page of Fiction should carry not too many categories so we should carefully choose them. We should also add several empty categories like Horror etc to attract co-workers to fill them in. For the visual layout i think we should follow the <a rel="nofollow" class="external free" href="http://www.delphi-jedi.org/">http://www.delphi-jedi.org/</a> design. It is visually rich and pleasing which is an important factor for ease of use. I have already asked if we can get the nice round picture frame and maybe help in creating the icons (i am member of Project Jedi). I got an answer already with all we need to create our own icons.</p>
<p>Maybe i will find time tomorrow to set up a rough design in my sandbox.</p>
<p><a href="/wiki/User:Robert_Marquardt" title="User:Robert Marquardt">Robert Marquardt</a> 10:38, 9 December 2006 (EST)
</p>
<dl><dd>Don't forget Poetry. <a href="/wiki/User:Ricdiogo" title="User:Ricdiogo">Ricdiogo</a> 12:52, 9 December 2006 (EST)</dd></dl>
<dl><dd> 1) Real estate on the sidebar is limited, so don't count on putting many links there.</dd>
<dd> 2) I think fiction and non-fiction are quite useless categories because they are already implicated in many categories, like Crime Fiction, Science Fiction, Fantasy. Nobody would look for a non-fiction book in category: Fantasy.</dd>
<dd> 3) Categories allow for more diverse than just tree structures. One category can be a child of many parents. Like "England -- Social life and customs -- 19th century -- Fiction" can be a child of "social life" "British Literature" and "19th century Literature".</dd>
<dd> 4) The wikipedia policy for categories is that an entry should not be listed in a category <i>and</i> a sub-category thereof. So detective fiction books would not be listed again under crime fiction. I vote to follow wikipedia policies when there is no very good reason to do otherwise. Of course the same book can be listed in many unrelated categories.</dd>
<dd> 5) Make sure you use only GPLed or better icons. Also, the icon idea works well for some categories, like the deerstalker for detective fiction, but what icon could we use for 18th century British social drama? <a href="/wiki/User:Marcello" title="User:Marcello">Marcello</a> 13:55, 9 December 2006 (EST)</dd></dl>
<p><br />
</p>
<dl><dd> 1) I thought long about real estate vs an index page and in this case (if we implement it, see 2) the links won. If we place all Fiction and Non-Fiction links on a single page we get too many links and the page is not easily navigable anymore.</dd>
<dd> 2) I object. Fiction and Non-Fiction separates the users into readers for leisure and readers for work (more or less). It makes the pages easier to navigate by reducing the number of links and it allows to drop the word "Fiction" so "Crime Fiction" becomes "Crime". The icon frame could be colored to indicate Fiction vs Non-Fiction which provides information about where you are.</dd>
<dd> 3) This is a tree like a Unix file system. The only limitation would be that no up-links are allowed to avoid endless recursion. A user could otherwise get lost in it.</dd>
<dd> 4) I did not know that. It brings up another problem though. An author can now be spread over several categories. We will then need more categories. I fear that the tree grows too big then to be easily navigable. We are between Scylla and Charibdis though. Lets implement something and see how it works.</dd>
<dd> 5) I intend to create the icons myself so the license is no problem. For too specialized categories a generic Gutenberg icon will be good enough. The main idea is to make the upeer pages of the tree as visually pleasing as possible to attract users.<br /><a href="/wiki/User:Robert_Marquardt" title="User:Robert Marquardt">Robert Marquardt</a> 02:09, 10 December 2006 (EST)</dd></dl>
<p><br />
</p>
<dl><dd> I have created a sample table here: <a href="/wiki/User:Robert_Marquardt" title="User:Robert Marquardt">Robert Marquardt</a>. I have also created a simple generic PG icon and sent it to Marcello (webmaster address).</dd>
<dd> How about creating a "Bookshelf Tree Test Area" link on the Bookshelf page? Each of us can then create his own tree on that page and we can discuss until we settle on a version. The Bookshelf page is continued in the current fashion to allow the work on the content to stay easily accessible.<br /><a href="/wiki/User:Robert_Marquardt" title="User:Robert Marquardt">Robert Marquardt</a> 07:26, 10 December 2006 (EST)</dd></dl>
<p><br />
</p>
<dl><dd><dl><dd> ... Re: Icons - I find icons to be more trouble then they are worth... too busy and detract from the actual content. Text labels are sufficent.</dd>
<dd> ... Re: Fic/Non-Fic - I also feel that there is no need to seperate out Fic from Non-Fic at a top level... there is nothing wrong with having a page with a long category index (as long as it is in alphabetical order)... Seeing <i>Science</i> next to <i>Science Fiction</i> would not likely be confusing ... of course, if the PG books were cataloged properly in the first place, we wouldn't need to bother with bookshelves because we'd be able to perform appropriate searches in the database in the first place. (FYI: I'm a catalog librarian in "real life" =) <a href="/wiki/User:Thistlechick" title="User:Thistlechick">Thistlechick</a> 11:09, 11 December 2006 (EST)</dd></dl></dd></dl>
<p><br />
</p>
<dl><dd><dl><dd> The icons are for making the page visually attractive and for reducing the number of links to encourage a structured design. I think we will have to implement  more levels of the tree first to see how it works out. I can live without icons, but we will definitely need more structure than alphabetical labels if the number of categories grows. Fic vs Non-Fic seems dead, but something will be needed anyway. This will allow to add other categorizations than by genre on this page. See Online catalog link on the main page for the categorizations by language and by data type. If we mix them up with the genres in an alphabetical list it will become hard to navigate because the user has to unwrap the mixup of categorization classes.</dd>
<dd> The good thing about the Bookshelf is that PG can plunder it to improve the cataloging. The work on it also uncovers errors in the database. In Talk:Science Fiction -&gt; misc questions i have already posted two of them.</dd></dl></dd></dl>
<p><a href="/wiki/User:Robert_Marquardt" title="User:Robert Marquardt">Robert Marquardt</a> 11:44, 11 December 2006 (EST)
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Languages">Languages</span></h2>
<p>I just created <a href="/wiki/Christianity_(Bookshelf)" title="Christianity (Bookshelf)">Christianity (Bookshelf)</a> and added a Danish version of the Bible.  A bit later I noticed that <a href="/wiki/PT_Poesia_(Prateleira)" title="PT Poesia (Prateleira)">PT Poesia (Prateleira)</a> existed.  Should bookshelves be single language? Besides original texts such as an Arabic Qur'an definitely belongs on all language bookshelves since it is a founding work... or so I think.  Comments? Has this been decided? <a href="/wiki/User:Grenavitar" title="User:Grenavitar">Grenavitar</a> 03:01, 29 December 2006 (EST)
</p>
<dl><dd> Currently a Bookshelf page carries all books for the category. I think it should stay that way for any language version of PG. Otherwise most of the non-english Bookshelf pages would be empty.<br />BTW i just added a big chunk of bibles. <a href="/wiki/User:Robert_Marquardt" title="User:Robert Marquardt">Robert Marquardt</a> 03:12, 29 December 2006 (EST)</dd></dl>
<dl><dd>Books can be categorized in both bookshelves (in the main Bookshelf and in the language version.) The Bookshelf can carry <i>all the books</i>, but the language bookshelves can carry only <i>some of</i> the books in that given language. Nothing prevents a language of not having a bookshelf for a given category or having only one book in it. For a Portuguese speaker is easier to find a Port. poetry book in PT Poesia (Prateleira) than in Poetry (Bookshelf).  <a href="/wiki/User:Ricdiogo" title="User:Ricdiogo">Ricdiogo</a> 16:46, 29 December 2006 (EST)</dd></dl>
<p>I would prefer that english books are listed anyway. Most of the languages simply do not have enough books for a bookshelf. This is the decision of the language maintainer though. A link to the english bookshelf page or showing the books in the language first and the english books at the end of the page. It probably depends also on the amount of extra text on the english page. Simple book listings like now can be linked to. Elaborate text could be translated. <a href="/wiki/User:Robert_Marquardt" title="User:Robert Marquardt">Robert Marquardt</a> 00:45, 30 December 2006 (EST)
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Religion_Bookshelf">Religion Bookshelf</span></h2>
<p>I think we should create a "Religion (Bookshelf)" page and put links to the religion pages on it. That would be the first step towards a tree organization of the bookshelf. Also how about using the Wiki subpages feature? <a href="/wiki/User:Robert_Marquardt" title="User:Robert Marquardt">Robert Marquardt</a> 04:14, 4 January 2007 (EST)
</p>
<dl><dd>I had thought of a "Wikipedia-like" organization--but I recall seeing somewhere that someone wanted there not to be many subdirectories because it would make it more difficult to browse.  I have thought for a while now of creating Bookshelf which could be organized into sections.  Religion, Social Sciences, Literature, etc.  It would be simple enough to do and some might appreciate it.</dd>
<dd>Another option would be keeping all bookshelves in <a href="/wiki/Category:Bookshelf" title="Category:Bookshelf">Category:Bookshelf</a> but also adding other categories like Category:Religious Bookshelves.  As of now all bookshelves are only in one category and could easily be in more.  This way people could browse a comprehensive list or a particular list--depending on their fancies.</dd>
<dd>I think using the subpage feature is inadvisable because it doesn't allow for growth.  As of now Christianity would be a subpage of religion and Christmas a subpage of Christianity.  But, in the future as Gutenberg grows let's say we have Category:Holidays bookshelves because we now have dozens of books on Diwali, Passover, Eid.  It can't be a subpage to both even though it is a sub idea of both.  Not that I'm really advocating anything too complex--since the goal seemed to be to keep it simple. <a href="/wiki/User:Grenavitar" title="User:Grenavitar">Grenavitar</a> 06:55, 4 January 2007 (EST)</dd></dl>
<p>How about a limited tree structure for some areas? Religion is such a candidate because it is cleanly structured. The Religion page has the links to the specific religious page and can also carry text about the relation of the religions. <a href="/wiki/User:Robert_Marquardt" title="User:Robert Marquardt">Robert Marquardt</a> 01:45, 6 January 2007 (EST)
</p>
<dl><dd>The LoCC records should be plundered. Especially for Christianity there are several entries in "Advanced Search" which lead to works which should added to the Christianity (Bookshelf). Also the LOCC categories for Christianity are a good guide for reorganizing that bookshelf <a href="/wiki/User:Robert_Marquardt" title="User:Robert Marquardt">Robert Marquardt</a> 10:16, 2 February 2007 (EST)</dd></dl>
<p>I notice that in July, the Book of Mormon was removed with a comment that "Mormons are not Christians!!!".  In early December, another LDS related book was removed.  I don't want to start any holy wars here (I'm not Christian nor Mormon and hence have no horse in this race); but, this seems problematic to me.  Mormons do consider themselves Christians. The Wikipedia article from which the intro to the page is taken considers them Christians. Of course, others disagree.
</p><p>If we're going to categorize religions, it seems to me that it would be best to categorize them based on the opinions of the believers of the specific religion in question.
</p><p>Comments?  Other opinions?
</p><p><a href="//www.gutenberg.org/w/index.php?title=User:Audreyii&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="User:Audreyii (page does not exist)">Audreyii</a> 14:05, 7 December 2007 (EST)
</p>
<dl><dd>It was <a href="/wiki/User:Freeelf" title="User:Freeelf">User:Freeelf</a>, so I am sure he did it in good faith.  We need to avoid these opinions issues and go to self-definition.  My professor told me the other day that he didn't think Catholics were considered Christians--not in a mean, way, but that's what he thought.  But, I am sure we will keep them on the shelf.  Here is my justification for re-adding them.  1) They are a clear offshoot of Christianity 2) they self-identify as Christian and 3) Library of Congress classification lists them as BX which is "Christian Denominations".  Also, I am commenting on <a href="/wiki/Talk:Christianity_(Bookshelf)" title="Talk:Christianity (Bookshelf)">Talk:Christianity (Bookshelf)</a>. <a href="/wiki/User:Grenavitar" title="User:Grenavitar">Grenavitar</a> 14:25, 9 December 2007 (EST)</dd></dl>
