<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Holocaust.2C_Precursors_.28Bookshelf.29">Holocaust, Precursors (Bookshelf)</span></h2>
<p>I think this should be discussed.  It seems a little problematic to me because... not all links are clear and we are linking authors (without benefit of explanation) to a genocide.  I am curious to see what others think. <a href="/wiki/User:Grenavitar" title="User:Grenavitar">Grenavitar</a> 23:52, 20 January 2007 (EST)
</p>
<dl><dd> Maybe change to "Racism (Bookshelf)" and make Holocaust a section on the page. It would also allow to add the numerous texts about slavery. I think for now we should simply wait and see. <a href="/wiki/Islam_(Bookshelf)" title="Islam (Bookshelf)">Islam (Bookshelf)</a> worked well. I expected flamewars there already. <a href="/wiki/User:Robert_Marquardt" title="User:Robert Marquardt">Robert Marquardt</a> 00:21, 21 January 2007 (EST)</dd></dl>
<dl><dd><dl><dd>But Islam is a subject people write about.  You get flame wars discussing Islam--but people won't say that Robert Spencer books aren't about Islam; they'd say they are misinformed.  People didn't write about the Holocaust before 1922... for good reason and I find it a little worrisome to link certain authors to the Holocaust in such a way.  Eugenics was related to the Holocaust, but not all Eugenics is a precursor and I think a lot of people involved in Eugenics would probably have been horrified by the Holocaust.  It's just too much independent viewpoint and research to do that.  Now, if there is a Library of Congress subject marker talking about precursors and he can make it clear that it is being used, then I'd have no problem.  But, these are bookshelves, and we should be using notable classification systems for this--I think.  But, no flamewar... there aren't even enough editors yet&#160;:)  --<a href="/wiki/User:Grenavitar" title="User:Grenavitar">Grenavitar</a> 05:21, 21 January 2007 (EST)</dd></dl></dd></dl>
<dl><dd> This is why i think the page should get a new name and a reorganization. Holocaust as title is too narrow. It belongs to a subsection of Antisemitism.</dd></dl>
<p>Lets wait a day or two for Wikijeff to enter this discussion and if he does not comment then we should do the change ourselves.
The books need comments why they are listed. Darwin should be added because "On the Origin of Species" is the base for some racist theories. <a href="/wiki/User:Robert_Marquardt" title="User:Robert Marquardt">Robert Marquardt</a> 06:36, 21 January 2007 (EST)
</p>
<dl><dd><dl><dd> I don't think that a scientific theory that is true (except in Kentucky) deserves to be mentioned in this category. The bible is the base for many more racist ideas than Darwin's book, so if we put in Darwin we have to also put in the bible, the coran, etc. <a href="/wiki/User:Marcello" title="User:Marcello">Marcello</a> 16:21, 27 January 2007 (EST)</dd></dl></dd></dl>
<dl><dd> I agree that "Racism (Bookshelf)" would be a good way to handle this so that we have larger topics on the category page with subcategories included on the actual bookshelf... allows for less overwhelming browsing. <a href="/wiki/User:Thistlechick" title="User:Thistlechick">Thistlechick</a> 15:00, 24 January 2007 (EST)</dd></dl>
<dl><dd><dl><dd>Well, even that is slightly problematic.  For most of our non-fiction bookshelves they are about their titles.  Islam (Bookshelf) is books about Islam.  There aren't many books about racism... so would we be classifying books on Racism (Bookshelf) as being racist?  Although, say, Mein Kampf is pretty racist... not all lines are that clear... and it becomes problematic.  I think the Library of Congress is smart because their subject classification for Mein Kampf is merely "Germany--Politics and government--20th century."  I worry that if we get into classifying books as racist or sexist instead of classifying books on those subjects then we will run into problems.  That is my problem with Holocaust precursors.  We are saying "these books helped lead to the Holocaust" instead of what the books are about.  As a reliable subject guide we should say what books are about and avoid the other political questions. There are plenty of sources that will people decide if a book influenced the Holocaust or sexism or racism in America--we don't need to tell people.  But we can point them to books about racism or sexism or the Holocaust.  I think this is of fundamental importance so I'd like to hear if people agree or disagree. <a href="/wiki/User:Grenavitar" title="User:Grenavitar">Grenavitar</a> 15:11, 27 January 2007 (EST)</dd></dl></dd></dl>
<dl><dd><dl><dd><dl><dd> "Racism (Bookshelf)" should contain books about racism. Racist books should go into "Racist Books (Bookshelf)". Next we'll need "Books with Factual Inaccuracies". This is a easy one, just put every book in there and you're done. Just kidding. How are we going to decide if a book is racist or not? I'm for deleting the Holocaust bookshelf or make it into a user bookshelf. <a href="/wiki/User:Marcello" title="User:Marcello">Marcello</a> 16:21, 27 January 2007 (EST)</dd></dl></dd></dl></dd></dl>
<p>Alright folks, I'll give my two-cents as to why I created this bookshelf, and some explanation as well. Let me start off by saying I thought this bookshelf would be controversial for sure, but I have no intention of making it a personal soap-box. Indeed one of my reasons for doing this was because WWI seems to be well covered but WWII is not (in any obvious way) by PG texts. This has everything to do with the fact that many good, and not so good books on the subject are still copyrighted and nothing more. However, things that lead up to those unfortunate events (in one way or another) are old enough to be in PD, and many are on PG.
</p><p>I wanted to put all of the works that I could find in one place on PG for example: The theory of Evolution led (with some modification by others) rather directly to the idea that some of us are more "evolved" then the rest of us (Eugenics). But also, the Theosophical Society took Hitler under its wing and made him as messianic figure (hence Hitler's obsession with the Occult). There are other things too--religious movements within Christendom perpetuated by the Nazi's, and some play (I forget which one--if someone knows comment) that lead Hitler to kill a close relative (his cousin, I think). No easy way availed it self to tie this complex web of information available (now or in the future) on PG save a bookshelf.
</p><p>For the record, the Holocaust precursor is just a skeleton of major points that hit me at the time. I have every intention--with community support--of writing small bits of information as to what the Theory of Evolution is doing next to the work of an eccentric occultist. And moreover what a Christian religious movement that teaches the Christian "Church" has replaced "Israel" and "the Jews" as God's Chosen People has to do with the rest of it. Because, you are right, in the absence of additional explanation the list is confusing. I just have not had the luxury of the time (due to my work schedule) to put the explanatory matter before each section so the reader has some clue how these subjects connect.
</p><p>If it is possible for the Bookshelf to stay, and be developed (with the necessary amount of commentary) by the community I'd love to see it. I'm open to more discussion on this matter. I hope I've been both clear and reasonable. And thanks to <i>Grenavitar</i> for bringing this conversation to my attention. &#8212;<a href="/wiki/User:Wikijeff" title="User:Wikijeff">Wikijeff</a> 17:16, 27 January 2007 (EST).
</p>
<dl><dd>As long as you do not abandon your bookshelf we can wait for the information added. I think renaming it to "Racism (Bookshelf)" is still the way to go.</dd>
<dd>Holocaust can then be added as a category where you can write as much text as you want. I do not mind controversies over the content as long as it is not about text quality or poor organzation. A section about slavery would be nice. <a href="/wiki/User:Robert_Marquardt" title="User:Robert Marquardt">Robert Marquardt</a> 01:15, 28 January 2007 (EST)</dd></dl>
