<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="1_line_2_line">1 line 2 line</span></h2>
<p>On <a href="/wiki/Crime_Nonfiction_(Bookshelf)" title="Crime Nonfiction (Bookshelf)">Crime Nonfiction (Bookshelf)</a> and many other bookshelves I've seen books where the subtitles go to the second line.  I have been wanting to change this to Title: Subtitle to save some space but never wanted to without first asking.  So, now I'm asking.  I think it would look better and keep information tighter.  Agree? Disagree? <a href="/wiki/User:Grenavitar" title="User:Grenavitar">Grenavitar</a> 00:18, 2 February 2007 (EST)
</p><p>I prefer the title as it is in the database (sometimes with 4 lines!). The reason is that often enough the book titles have spelling errors (see Periodicals). Soon enough we should start an initiative to clean up the database entries of the books (and adding the metadata won through the bookshelves).<br />
By no means i advocate that we should use the titles in only one way. Feel free to experiment. <a href="/wiki/User:Robert_Marquardt" title="User:Robert Marquardt">Robert Marquardt</a> 02:47, 2 February 2007 (EST)
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Love">Love</span></h2>
<p>I created <a href="/wiki/Love_(Bookshelf)" title="Love (Bookshelf)">Love (Bookshelf)</a> since it seemed topical and the Christmas Bookshelf seemed to be a hit.  I was hoping to find more non-fiction (and one of them is about Godly love, which is all well and good, but not as topical).  In any case, I created it just the same... I didn't put any fiction because... what's the difference between love and romance and just an ordinary novel with a love story?  I wanted to post here for input and also... so someone can delete / move it if they find a better title. <a href="/wiki/User:Grenavitar" title="User:Grenavitar">Grenavitar</a> 00:30, 12 February 2007 (EST)
